{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0167PgbvxGvH7NwRVf7SRSLy","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Retrospective written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/epic-10-retrospective.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Epic 10 delivered the Stack Provider Pattern in 5 stories over ~2.5 hours. The codebase went from 8+ files with scattered `if (stack === 'nodejs')` conditionals to 3 centralized provider files behind a 16-method interface. `src/lib/stack-detect.ts` (283 lines) was deleted. 245 net new tests (3,153 -> 3,398), zero regressions, coverage held steady at 96.98% statements / 88.42% branches. A boundary test permanently enforces that stack conditionals stay inside `src/lib/stacks/`.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Recurring pattern -- CoverageToolName type fragmentation:**\nThe `CoverageToolName` values returned by providers (`'tarpaulin'`, `'coverage-py'`) don't match the strings stored in `HarnessState.coverage.tool` (`'cargo-tarpaulin'`, `'coverage.py'`). This forced story 10-5 to use a hardcoded dispatch map instead of clean provider delegation. Same issue surfaced in Epic 9. This is now blocking clean provider adoption in `coverage.ts`.\n- **Action (immediate):** Add to Epic 14 backlog if not already tracked. Should be fixed before any new stack is added.\n\n**Story 10-5 was the hardest -- expected but still heavy:**\n10-5 touched 8 consumer files, deleted 2 files, updated imports across 11+ test files, and created a boundary test. It was correctly scoped as the \"big bang\" migration story, but at 17 ACs it was the densest story in the epic. The `otlp.ts` migration alone had ~10 separate conditionals.\n- **Action (backlog):** For future migration epics, consider splitting the \"migrate consumers\" story by consumer file count (e.g., max 5 files per story).\n\n**Dispatch maps are a half-measure:**\nMultiple consumers replaced `if/else` chains with `{ nodejs: ..., python: ..., rust: ... }` object maps. These still enumerate all stacks explicitly. The boundary test doesn't catch them because they use stack names as object keys, not `=== 'nodejs'` comparisons. When a 4th stack is added, these maps need manual updates.\n- **Action (process/tooling):** Consider adding a boundary test pattern that checks for `nodejs.*python.*rust` key patterns in object literals outside `src/lib/stacks/`. Low priority but would prevent silent omissions.\n\n**Pre-existing TS compilation errors (~100 lines) still not fixed:**\nThese have persisted across Epics 8, 9, and 10. Every story's `tsc --noEmit` check reports them. They're in `bridge.test.ts` and `run.test.ts`.\n- **Action (immediate):** Prioritize `15-4-fix-ts-compilation-errors` in the next sprint. This is noise that makes it harder to detect real type regressions."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a6eaae96a33158ff6 (use SendMessage with to: 'a6eaae96a33158ff6' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 37338\ntool_uses: 20\nduration_ms: 124727</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6707468c-554d-4568-9ea5-0d04d4a85f59","uuid":"40f20c12-e608-4742-b69a-3633d3bc2004","timestamp":"2026-03-24T10:16:13.630Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /retrospective for Epic 10. All stories are complete. Review the epic's work, extract lessons learned, and produce the retrospective document. \n\nEpic 10 is \"Stack Provider Pattern\" with stories:\n- 10-1-stackprovider-interface-and-registry\n- 10-2-nodejs-provider\n- 10-3-python-provider\n- 10-4-rust-provider\n- 10-5-migrate-consumers-to-stackprovider\n\nThe sprint status is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml.\nSession issues from this epic's stories are in _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/.session-issues.md (look for 10-* entries).\n\nAlso check git log for the epic's commits.\n\nDo NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Epic-level problems (recurring patterns across stories, process breakdowns)\n- Stories that were harder than expected and why\n- Action items that need immediate attention vs. backlog\n- Process improvements that should be encoded in tooling/config, not just documented\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a6eaae96a33158ff6","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Retrospective written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/epic-10-retrospective.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Epic 10 delivered the Stack Provider Pattern in 5 stories over ~2.5 hours. The codebase went from 8+ files with scattered `if (stack === 'nodejs')` conditionals to 3 centralized provider files behind a 16-method interface. `src/lib/stack-detect.ts` (283 lines) was deleted. 245 net new tests (3,153 -> 3,398), zero regressions, coverage held steady at 96.98% statements / 88.42% branches. A boundary test permanently enforces that stack conditionals stay inside `src/lib/stacks/`.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Recurring pattern -- CoverageToolName type fragmentation:**\nThe `CoverageToolName` values returned by providers (`'tarpaulin'`, `'coverage-py'`) don't match the strings stored in `HarnessState.coverage.tool` (`'cargo-tarpaulin'`, `'coverage.py'`). This forced story 10-5 to use a hardcoded dispatch map instead of clean provider delegation. Same issue surfaced in Epic 9. This is now blocking clean provider adoption in `coverage.ts`.\n- **Action (immediate):** Add to Epic 14 backlog if not already tracked. Should be fixed before any new stack is added.\n\n**Story 10-5 was the hardest -- expected but still heavy:**\n10-5 touched 8 consumer files, deleted 2 files, updated imports across 11+ test files, and created a boundary test. It was correctly scoped as the \"big bang\" migration story, but at 17 ACs it was the densest story in the epic. The `otlp.ts` migration alone had ~10 separate conditionals.\n- **Action (backlog):** For future migration epics, consider splitting the \"migrate consumers\" story by consumer file count (e.g., max 5 files per story).\n\n**Dispatch maps are a half-measure:**\nMultiple consumers replaced `if/else` chains with `{ nodejs: ..., python: ..., rust: ... }` object maps. These still enumerate all stacks explicitly. The boundary test doesn't catch them because they use stack names as object keys, not `=== 'nodejs'` comparisons. When a 4th stack is added, these maps need manual updates.\n- **Action (process/tooling):** Consider adding a boundary test pattern that checks for `nodejs.*python.*rust` key patterns in object literals outside `src/lib/stacks/`. Low priority but would prevent silent omissions.\n\n**Pre-existing TS compilation errors (~100 lines) still not fixed:**\nThese have persisted across Epics 8, 9, and 10. Every story's `tsc --noEmit` check reports them. They're in `bridge.test.ts` and `run.test.ts`.\n- **Action (immediate):** Prioritize `15-4-fix-ts-compilation-errors` in the next sprint. This is noise that makes it harder to detect real type regressions."}],"totalDurationMs":124727,"totalTokens":37338,"totalToolUseCount":20,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2820,"cache_read_input_tokens":33776,"output_tokens":741,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2820},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
