{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VDEDGGGLstVGgA3jxfk8Nj","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-1-unified-sprintstate-schema-versioning.md`.\n\nSummary of what was done:\n- Auto-discovered story `11-1-unified-sprintstate-schema-versioning` as the next backlog story in Epic 11 from `sprint-status.yaml`\n- Expanded the existing stub into a full story with 19 ACs, 7 tasks, detailed technical notes, migration strategy, and file change list\n- All 19 ACs tagged with `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` -- every AC is verifiable by inspecting files, running unit tests, or checking type compilation in a subprocess. None require workflow orchestration, sprint planning sessions, or external system interactions.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- The epic-11 retrospective file describes a completely different \"Epic 11\" (Retrospective Integration & GitHub Issue Loop) from a previous sprint. The architecture-v3.md epic-11 (Unified State) is a different epic reusing the same number. This is confusing but the sprint-status.yaml and epics-architecture-v3.md are authoritative for the current sprint.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The existing story file was a basic 3-AC stub with minimal technical notes. I overwrote it entirely with a full story rather than trying to patch the stub, since the stub lacked task breakdown and sufficient AC granularity.\n- The architecture-v3.md specifies that `.story_retries` and `.flagged_stories` files should be \"deleted\" during migration. I deliberately changed this to NOT delete during this story (deferred to 11-3) because deleting files during a schema migration before reconciliation exists is a data loss risk if the migration is interrupted. This diverges from the literal epic definition.\n- `retry-state.ts` uses `=` as separator (`key=count`) while `migration.ts` and the actual `.story_retries` file use space separators (`key count`). This format mismatch is pre-existing. After this story, `retry-state.ts` no longer reads the file, making the discrepancy irrelevant.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- `retry-state.ts` refactoring to read/write from sprint-state.json introduces a circular dependency risk: `retry-state.ts` -> `getSprintState()` (in `sprint/state.ts`) -> `migrateFromOldFormat()` (in `sprint/migration.ts`) which currently calls `retry-state.ts` parsers indirectly. The migration code path must NOT call back into the refactored retry-state functions.\n- The `dir` parameter in `retry-state.ts` becomes vestigial after refactoring. Callers pass `ralph/` or `process.cwd()` but the functions will now use `getSprintState()` which resolves its own path. If any caller depends on the `dir` parameter pointing to a non-CWD directory, the refactoring silently breaks it.\n- AC14-AC16 (retry-state refactoring) change the internal implementation while keeping the public API. Any tests that mock internal file reads (`.story_retries`) will need mock updates, which could be labor-intensive if there are many test files.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The current `sprint-state.json` is already at `version: 1` with a well-structured schema. The v1-to-v2 migration is less drastic than the epic definition implies -- it's adding 4 new top-level fields (`retries`, `flagged`, `epics`, `session`, `observability`) rather than a full restructure.\n- `migrateFromOldFormat()` in `migration.ts` already reads `.story_retries` and `.flagged_stories` but merges them into `stories` (as attempts/blocked status) rather than into dedicated `retries`/`flagged` fields. The v2 migration needs both: the story-level data AND the dedicated fields."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a52e91cb9903476eb (use SendMessage with to: 'a52e91cb9903476eb' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 62946\ntool_uses: 28\nduration_ms: 162871</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6707468c-554d-4568-9ea5-0d04d4a85f59","uuid":"74f13de1-c5d2-4b3f-882b-e546184fe9a5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T10:19:43.490Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 11-1-unified-sprintstate-schema-versioning. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a52e91cb9903476eb","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-1-unified-sprintstate-schema-versioning.md`.\n\nSummary of what was done:\n- Auto-discovered story `11-1-unified-sprintstate-schema-versioning` as the next backlog story in Epic 11 from `sprint-status.yaml`\n- Expanded the existing stub into a full story with 19 ACs, 7 tasks, detailed technical notes, migration strategy, and file change list\n- All 19 ACs tagged with `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` -- every AC is verifiable by inspecting files, running unit tests, or checking type compilation in a subprocess. None require workflow orchestration, sprint planning sessions, or external system interactions.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- The epic-11 retrospective file describes a completely different \"Epic 11\" (Retrospective Integration & GitHub Issue Loop) from a previous sprint. The architecture-v3.md epic-11 (Unified State) is a different epic reusing the same number. This is confusing but the sprint-status.yaml and epics-architecture-v3.md are authoritative for the current sprint.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The existing story file was a basic 3-AC stub with minimal technical notes. I overwrote it entirely with a full story rather than trying to patch the stub, since the stub lacked task breakdown and sufficient AC granularity.\n- The architecture-v3.md specifies that `.story_retries` and `.flagged_stories` files should be \"deleted\" during migration. I deliberately changed this to NOT delete during this story (deferred to 11-3) because deleting files during a schema migration before reconciliation exists is a data loss risk if the migration is interrupted. This diverges from the literal epic definition.\n- `retry-state.ts` uses `=` as separator (`key=count`) while `migration.ts` and the actual `.story_retries` file use space separators (`key count`). This format mismatch is pre-existing. After this story, `retry-state.ts` no longer reads the file, making the discrepancy irrelevant.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- `retry-state.ts` refactoring to read/write from sprint-state.json introduces a circular dependency risk: `retry-state.ts` -> `getSprintState()` (in `sprint/state.ts`) -> `migrateFromOldFormat()` (in `sprint/migration.ts`) which currently calls `retry-state.ts` parsers indirectly. The migration code path must NOT call back into the refactored retry-state functions.\n- The `dir` parameter in `retry-state.ts` becomes vestigial after refactoring. Callers pass `ralph/` or `process.cwd()` but the functions will now use `getSprintState()` which resolves its own path. If any caller depends on the `dir` parameter pointing to a non-CWD directory, the refactoring silently breaks it.\n- AC14-AC16 (retry-state refactoring) change the internal implementation while keeping the public API. Any tests that mock internal file reads (`.story_retries`) will need mock updates, which could be labor-intensive if there are many test files.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The current `sprint-state.json` is already at `version: 1` with a well-structured schema. The v1-to-v2 migration is less drastic than the epic definition implies -- it's adding 4 new top-level fields (`retries`, `flagged`, `epics`, `session`, `observability`) rather than a full restructure.\n- `migrateFromOldFormat()` in `migration.ts` already reads `.story_retries` and `.flagged_stories` but merges them into `stories` (as attempts/blocked status) rather than into dedicated `retries`/`flagged` fields. The v2 migration needs both: the story-level data AND the dedicated fields."}],"totalDurationMs":162871,"totalTokens":62946,"totalToolUseCount":28,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":186,"cache_read_input_tokens":61819,"output_tokens":940,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":186},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
