{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NgnQbes6DiPnk2goACh4U1","type":"tool_result","content":"   200→\n   201→### Avoid\n   202→- **Deferring too much scope to a single future story.** Story 10-5 now owns: type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), consumer migration, branch removal, and StackDetection deduplication. Consider splitting 10-5 into sub-stories before it starts.\n   203→- **Ignoring growing TS error counts.** 50 pre-existing type errors is no longer \"noise\" — it's a quality signal. Prioritize 15-4 or at least triage which errors are new vs. old.\n   204→\n   205→---\n   206→\n   207→## 6. Action Items\n   208→\n   209→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   210→- None critical. All HIGH/MEDIUM issues from 10-2 review are resolved. Story is functionally complete pending verification.\n   211→\n   212→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   213→1. **Complete story 10-3 (PythonProvider)** — Next in Epic 10 sequence.\n   214→2. **Triage pre-existing TS errors.** Determine whether the jump from ~10 to ~50 is real or a counting difference. If real, escalate story 15-4 priority.\n   215→3. **Consider splitting story 10-5.** It has at least 4 distinct responsibilities. Break into: (a) type reconciliation, (b) consumer migration, (c) branch cleanup, (d) deduplication cleanup.\n   216→4. **Verify story 10-2.** Run final verification pass to move from `verifying` to `done`.\n   217→\n   218→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   219→1. **`readTextSafe` catch branch coverage** — 93.33%, race condition edge case. Not worth the mock complexity.\n   220→2. **`registry.ts` coverage gap at 94.73%** — Lines from story 10-1, will naturally improve as more providers register.\n   221→3. **`patchStartScript` optional chaining documentation** — Ensure consumer migration in 10-5 uses `?.` consistently.\n   222→4. All items from session 8 backlog remain open (15-4, 15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test).\n   223→\n   224→---\n   225→\n   226→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-24 (Session 10)\n   227→\n   228→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence (Architecture v3 Migration phase)\n   229→**Session:** 10 (autonomous ralph run, continuation from session 9)\n   230→**Session start:** ~08:19 UTC\n   231→**Appended:** 2026-03-24\n   232→\n   233→---\n   234→\n   235→## 1. Session Summary\n   236→\n   237→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Pipeline Stages Completed |\n   238→|-------|------|---------|---------------------------|\n   239→| 10-3-python-provider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | verifying (blocked) | create-story, dev-story, code-review, verification (failed) |\n   240→\n   241→Story 10-3 was the sole story attempted. Ralph selected it as the next Tier D backlog item after 10-2 completed in session 9. The story went through all four pipeline stages: story creation (~08:23Z), development (~08:28Z, 62 new tests, 3329 total, 0 regressions), code review (~08:33Z, 4 issues found — 3 HIGH/MEDIUM fixed, 2 LOW deferred), and verification (~08:38Z). Verification **failed** due to Docker Desktop not running — `codeharness stack start` could not launch the observability stack.\n   242→\n   243→**Net progress:** Epic 10 now has 2 of 5 stories done (10-1, 10-2), 1 in verifying/blocked (10-3). Stories 10-4 (Rust) and 10-5 (consumer migration) remain in backlog. Sprint-state shows 10-3 at status `review` (discrepancy with sprint-status.yaml which shows `verifying`).\n   244→\n   245→---\n   246→\n   247→## 2. Issues Analysis\n   248→\n   249→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Verification\n   250→\n   251→| Severity | Story | Issue | Fixed? |\n   252→|----------|-------|-------|--------|\n   253→| HIGH | 10-3 | `detectCoverageConfig` substring false positives — `String.includes('coverage')` matched unrelated packages like `coverage-conditional-plugin` | Yes — switched to `hasPythonDep()` |\n   254→| MEDIUM | 10-3 | `installOtlp` pipx fallback lost track of partially installed packages | Yes |\n   255→| MEDIUM | 10-3 | `getProjectName` TOML regex crossed section boundaries, extracting wrong values | Yes |\n   256→| MEDIUM | 10-3 | Missing direct tests for `getPythonDepsContent()` and `hasPythonDep()` — 13 tests added | Yes |\n   257→\n   258→Code review caught 4 issues (1 HIGH, 3 MEDIUM). All fixed in-session. The `detectCoverageConfig` false positive was the most concerning — it would have incorrectly reported coverage tool presence for projects that merely depend on a package with \"coverage\" in its name.\n   259→\n   260→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n   261→\n   262→1. **Epic mentions CLI/library detection for Python app types, but codebase only supports agent/web/server/generic.** ACs were written to reflect actual code, not the aspirational epic text. The epic's scope exceeds what the codebase currently models.\n   263→2. **`getProjectName()` uses TOML regex instead of a proper TOML parser.** Fragile for edge cases (multi-line values, inline tables). Adding a TOML parser dependency was rejected as overkill for this use case, but the regex was tightened to not cross section boundaries.\n   264→3. **`hasPythonDep()` regex is fragile for packages with hyphens/underscores.** Python normalizes `foo-bar` and `foo_bar` as equivalent; the current regex does not. Low real-world impact since the specific packages checked (`pytest`, `opentelemetry-distro`, etc.) have canonical names.\n   265→4. **`hasPythonDep` matches package names inside comments.** Pre-existing behavior from the pattern used in other providers. Low real-world impact.\n   266→\n   267→### Code Quality Concerns\n   268→\n   269→1. **`PYTHON_OTLP_PACKAGES` values differ from original story skeleton.** Code uses `opentelemetry-distro`/`opentelemetry-exporter-otlp` (correct), not what was originally specified. Story creation agent corrected this.\n   270→2. **Python has no `patchStartScript()`.** Uses `opentelemetry-instrument` wrapper via env vars instead. This is architecturally different from Node.js and means the `StackProvider.patchStartScript?` optional method pattern is validated — not all providers implement all methods.\n   271→3. **`installOtlp` success path untested.** Requires real `pip`/`pipx` binaries. Unit tests cover failure paths and argument construction but not actual package installation. This is a coverage gap that can only be closed with integration tests.\n   272→4. **Task comment markers in code could be cleaned up.** LOW priority, cosmetic.\n   273→\n   274→### Verification Gaps\n   275→\n   276→- **BLOCKER: Docker Desktop not running.** Verification requires `codeharness stack start` which depends on Docker. All 21 ACs are tagged `cli-verifiable` (unit-testable), suggesting the story does not actually need Docker for verification. The verification agent did not distinguish between the story's verification requirements and the infrastructure check.\n   277→- **Observation:** Story would benefit from a `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` tag to allow the verification agent to skip Docker requirements for pure unit-test stories.\n   278→\n   279→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n   280→\n   281→- **Docker Desktop unavailable.** This is the first Docker-related blocker in the current sprint. It prevented verification completion despite all code and tests being ready.\n   282→- **No other sandbox, permission, or CLI issues reported.**\n   283→\n   284→---\n   285→\n   286→## 3. What Went Well\n   287→\n   288→- **Full pipeline execution through 4 stages.** Story 10-3 completed create-story, dev-story, code-review, and attempted verification — the most complete pipeline run for a single story in this sprint.\n   289→- **Code review continues to find real bugs.** The `detectCoverageConfig` false positive (HIGH) would have been a production defect. Sessions 8, 9, and 10 have each had at least one HIGH-severity bug caught by review.\n   290→- **62 new tests with zero regressions.** 3329 total tests passing. The Python provider has thorough unit test coverage.\n   291→- **Story creation agent corrected inaccurate epic details.** The OTLP package names and the absence of `patchStartScript()` for Python were correctly identified and reflected in the ACs, rather than blindly implementing what the epic described.\n   292→- **Dev completed with no issues reported.** Clean implementation — all problems were found in review, not during development.\n   293→\n   294→---\n   295→\n   296→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   297→\n   298→- **Docker blocker prevented verification.** The story is code-complete and review-complete but cannot be marked done. This is wasted session time — the verification agent attempted Docker-dependent checks for a unit-testable story.\n   299→- **Verification agent lacks tier awareness.** All 21 ACs are `cli-verifiable` but the agent still required Docker. The harness-run pipeline does not currently use verification tier metadata to skip infrastructure checks.\n   300→- **Still only 1 story per session.** The pipeline (create + dev + review + verify) for a medium-complexity story consumes an entire ralph session. Epic 10 completion now requires at minimum 2 more sessions (10-4 + 10-5, assuming 10-3 verification can be done quickly).\n   301→- **State discrepancy.** `sprint-state.json` shows 10-3 at `review` while `sprint-status.yaml` shows `verifying`. The verification agent updated the YAML but not the JSON (or the JSON was updated to a different value).\n   302→\n   303→---\n   304→\n   305→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   306→\n   307→### Repeat\n   308→- **Story creation agents correcting epic inaccuracies.** The Python provider's architectural differences (no `patchStartScript`, different OTLP package names) were correctly captured at story creation time, preventing implementation confusion.\n   309→- **Tightening regex patterns during review.** The TOML regex section-boundary fix and the `detectCoverageConfig` switch to `hasPythonDep()` both improved correctness. Review-driven regex hardening is valuable.\n   310→- **Adding targeted tests for utility functions.** The 13 new tests for `getPythonDepsContent()` and `hasPythonDep()` filled a real gap.\n   311→\n   312→### Avoid\n   313→- **Running Docker-dependent verification for unit-testable stories.** The verification agent should check the story's verification tier before requiring Docker. This wasted the verification attempt and left the story in limbo.\n   314→- **Accepting fragile regex for structured data parsing.** The TOML regex was tightened but is still fundamentally fragile. If Python provider usage grows, a proper TOML parser should replace it.\n   315→- **Allowing state files to diverge.** `sprint-state.json` and `sprint-status.yaml` should always agree on story status. The pipeline should update both atomically or derive one from the other (story 11-2 addresses this but is backlogged).\n   316→\n   317→---\n   318→\n   319→## 6. Action Items\n   320→\n   321→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   322→1. **Start Docker Desktop.** Required to unblock 10-3 verification and any future stories needing `stack start`.\n   323→2. **Verify story 10-3.** With Docker available, run verification to move from `verifying` to `done`. All code and tests are ready.\n   324→3. **Reconcile state files.** Align `sprint-state.json` (shows `review`) with `sprint-status.yaml` (shows `verifying`) for story 10-3.\n   325→\n   326→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   327→1. **Complete story 10-4 (RustProvider).** Next in Epic 10 sequence.\n   328→2. **Add verification-tier awareness to the harness-run pipeline.** Stories tagged `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` should skip Docker checks. This would have prevented today's blocker.\n   329→3. **Consider splitting story 10-5.** Carried forward from session 9 — it has at least 4 responsibilities (type reconciliation, consumer migration, branch cleanup, deduplication). Risk of being too large for a single story.\n   330→4. **Address `hasPythonDep` hyphen/underscore normalization.** Python's PEP 503 normalization means `foo-bar` == `foo_bar` == `foo.bar`. Current regex does not handle this.\n   331→\n   332→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   333→1. **`installOtlp` success path integration test.** Needs real pip/pipx — only feasible in Docker or CI environment.\n   334→2. **Replace TOML regex with proper parser** if Python provider use cases expand beyond `getProjectName()`.\n   335→3. **Clean up task comment markers** in Python provider code.\n   336→4. **Story 15-4: Fix pre-existing TS compilation errors.** Still growing (~50 as of session 9). Noise is accumulating.\n   337→5. All items from sessions 8-9 backlog remain open (15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test, `_resetRegistry` export cleanup).\n   338→\n   339→---\n   340→\n   341→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-24 (Session 11)\n   342→\n   343→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence (Architecture v3 Migration phase)\n   344→**Session:** 11 (autonomous ralph run, continuation from session 10)\n   345→**Session start:** ~08:50 UTC\n   346→**Appended:** 2026-03-24\n   347→\n   348→---\n   349→\n   350→## 1. Session Summary\n   351→\n   352→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Pipeline Stages Completed |\n   353→|-------|------|---------|---------------------------|\n   354→| 10-3-python-provider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | done | verification (retry -- succeeded) |\n   355→\n   356→This was a short recovery session. Story 10-3 had been blocked at `verifying` since session 10 due to Docker Desktop being unavailable. Session 11 resolved the blocker by using unit-testable verification (the story was already tagged `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->`), bypassing Docker entirely. All 21 ACs passed. Story was committed as `ffb5429`.\n   357→\n   358→Additionally, the verification agent fixed a stale `AGENTS.md` (missing `python.ts` entry) and updated `utils.ts` description.\n   359→\n   360→**Net progress:** Epic 10 now has 3 of 5 stories done (10-1, 10-2, 10-3). Stories 10-4 (Rust) and 10-5 (consumer migration) remain in backlog.\n   361→\n   362→---\n   363→\n   364→## 2. Issues Analysis\n   365→\n   366→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Verification\n   367→\n   368→No new bugs discovered. All code-level issues were caught and fixed in session 10's code review.\n   369→\n   370→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n   371→\n   372→No new workarounds this session. All tech debt items from session 10 carry forward unchanged.\n   373→\n   374→### Code Quality Concerns\n   375→\n   376→1. **AGENTS.md was stale.** Missing the `python.ts` entry and `utils.ts` description was outdated. Fixed during verification. This is a recurring problem -- AGENTS.md is not automatically updated when new source files are added. Manual maintenance is error-prone.\n   377→\n   378→### Verification Gaps\n   379→\n   380→1. **Proof document format was wrong on first attempt.** The verification agent produced proof with incorrect formatting -- missing `bash`/`output` code blocks and wrong `**Tier:**` format. The `validateProofQuality()` parser in `src/modules/verify/proof.ts` requires specific format for evidence recognition. The agent had to study the parser source code and rewrite the proof.\n   381→2. **`codeharness verify` preconditions require both tests AND coverage.** Running `npm test` alone is not sufficient -- `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` must also run in the same session. This caught the verification agent off guard.\n   382→\n   383→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n   384→\n   385→1. **Docker Desktop still unavailable.** The blocker from session 10 was not resolved (Docker was not started). Instead, the verification approach was changed to unit-testable verification, which was the correct move since all 21 ACs were `cli-verifiable`.\n   386→2. **Proof parser is fragile and undocumented.** The verification agent had to reverse-engineer `validateProofQuality()` to produce correctly formatted proof. The expected format should be documented or the parser should provide better error messages.\n   387→\n   388→---\n   389→\n   390→## 3. What Went Well\n   391→\n   392→- **10-3 unblocked and completed.** The Docker blocker from session 10 was resolved without waiting for Docker -- the agent correctly identified that the story's verification tier (`unit-testable`) did not require Docker.\n   393→- **21/21 ACs passed.** Clean verification with no failures. All code review fixes from session 10 held up.\n   394→- **AGENTS.md updated.** A stale documentation gap was caught and fixed during verification.\n   395→- **Epic 10 at 60% completion.** Three of five stories done in a single day across sessions 8-11. The StackProvider pattern (interface, Node.js, Python) is fully implemented.\n   396→- **Test suite at 3329 tests, 0 regressions.** 231 new tests added across sessions 8-11 (from 3098 to 3329).\n   397→\n   398→---\n   399→\n   400→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   401→\n   402→- **Verification required two attempts.** The first attempt failed because the proof document format was wrong. The verification agent wasted time producing incorrectly formatted proof, then had to study the parser internals to understand the expected format. Better documentation of the proof format would prevent this.\n   403→- **Docker is still down.** Session 10's \"Fix Now\" action item (start Docker Desktop) was not addressed. The workaround worked for 10-3 but story 10-4 (Rust) may need Docker for integration-level verification.\n   404→- **State file discrepancy persisted.** Session 10 noted that `sprint-state.json` and `sprint-status.yaml` disagreed on 10-3 status. The verification agent updated `sprint-state.json` to `done` but the root cause -- no atomic state update between the two files -- remains.\n   405→\n   406→---\n   407→\n   408→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   409→\n   410→### Repeat\n   411→- **Using verification-tier metadata to skip infrastructure requirements.** The `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` tag saved this session. Stories with all `cli-verifiable` ACs should always use this pattern.\n   412→- **Studying parser expectations before producing formatted output.** The second verification attempt succeeded because the agent read `validateProofQuality()` first. Agents should always check format expectations before generating structured output.\n   413→\n   414→### Avoid\n   415→- **Generating proof documents without checking the expected format first.** The wasted first attempt was entirely avoidable. The proof format should either be documented in the story template or the verification agent should always read `src/modules/verify/proof.ts` before generating proof.\n   416→- **Leaving infrastructure blockers unresolved between sessions.** Docker was flagged as \"Fix Now\" in session 10 but not fixed. Action items marked \"Fix Now\" should be treated as prerequisites for the next session.\n   417→\n   418→---\n   419→\n   420→## 6. Action Items\n   421→\n   422→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   423→1. **Start Docker Desktop.** Carried forward from session 10. Required for any story needing `stack start` or integration tests.\n   424→2. **Document proof format expectations.** Either add format docs to the verification template or add better error messages to `validateProofQuality()` so agents do not have to reverse-engineer the parser.\n   425→\n   426→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   427→1. **Complete story 10-4 (RustProvider).** Next in Epic 10 sequence. Last provider implementation before consumer migration.\n   428→2. **Consider splitting story 10-5** before starting it. It accumulates: type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), consumer migration, branch cleanup, StackDetection dedup. At least 4 sub-stories.\n   429→3. **Auto-update AGENTS.md when new source files are added.** Either a pre-commit hook or a harness-run post-dev step. Manual maintenance is failing.\n   430→4. **Add verification-tier awareness to harness-run pipeline.** Stories tagged `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` should automatically skip Docker checks. This was the root cause of session 10's blocker.\n   431→\n   432→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   433→1. **`hasPythonDep` hyphen/underscore normalization** -- PEP 503 compliance. Low real-world impact with current package set.\n   434→2. **`installOtlp` success path integration test** -- Needs real pip/pipx. Only feasible in Docker/CI.\n   435→3. **Replace TOML regex with proper parser** -- If Python provider usage expands beyond `getProjectName()`.\n   436→4. **Story 15-4: Fix pre-existing TS compilation errors** -- ~50 errors as of session 9. Growing noise.\n   437→5. **Proof parser error messages** -- `validateProofQuality()` should explain what format it expects when validation fails.\n   438→6. All items from sessions 8-10 backlog remain open (15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test, `_resetRegistry` export cleanup, `readTextSafe` catch branch, `registry.ts` 94.73% coverage).\n   439→\n   440→---\n   441→\n   442→## Cross-Session Summary (Sessions 8-11, 2026-03-24)\n   443→\n   444→### Stories completed today: 3\n   445→- **10-1-stackprovider-interface-and-registry** -- done (session 8)\n   446→- **10-2-nodejs-provider** -- done (session 9)\n   447→- **10-3-python-provider** -- done (sessions 10-11)\n   448→\n   449→### Cumulative stats\n   450→- Tests: 3098 -> 3329 (+231 new tests)\n   451→- Bugs caught by code review: 15 (7 in session 8, 4 in session 9, 4 in session 10) -- all fixed\n   452→- Bugs shipped: 0\n   453→- Stories blocked: 0 (10-3 blocker resolved)\n   454→- Tech debt items deferred: 8 (type mismatches x2, regex fragility x2, comment matching, task markers, consumer branches, AGENTS.md staleness)\n   455→\n   456→### Sprint velocity\n   457→- Epic 10 progress: 0/5 -> 3/5 in one day\n   458→- Pipeline throughput: ~1 story per ralph session (consistent across all 4 sessions)\n   459→- Estimated sessions remaining for Epic 10: 2 (10-4 + 10-5, assuming 10-5 is not split)\n   460→\n   461→---\n   462→\n   463→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-24 (Sessions 12-13)\n   464→\n   465→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence (Architecture v3 Migration phase)\n   466→**Sessions:** 12 (10-4 full pipeline) and 13 (10-5 story creation + 10-4 verification)\n   467→**Session start:** ~09:14 UTC\n   468→**Appended:** 2026-03-24T13:11Z\n   469→\n   470→---\n   471→\n   472→## 1. Session Summary\n   473→\n   474→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Pipeline Stages Completed |\n   475→|-------|------|---------|---------------------------|\n   476→| 10-4-rust-provider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | done | create-story, dev-story, code-review, verification (implicit via commit) |\n   477→| 10-5-migrate-consumers-to-stackprovider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | ready-for-dev | create-story only |\n   478→\n   479→**Session 12 (~09:14-09:34Z):** Story 10-4 went through the full pipeline -- create-story, dev-story (55 new tests, 3397 total, 0 regressions), and code-review (2 MEDIUM fixed, 2 LOW deferred). Committed as `fa47c33`.\n   480→\n   481→**Session 13 (~09:43Z):** Story 10-5 had its create-story stage completed. The story creation agent expanded the backlog item into a detailed 17-AC spec covering consumer migration for all files that contain stack string comparisons. Story status moved from `backlog` to `ready-for-dev`.\n   482→\n   483→**Net progress:** Epic 10 now has 4 of 5 stories done (10-1, 10-2, 10-3, 10-4). Only 10-5 (consumer migration) remains, at `ready-for-dev`.\n   484→\n   485→---\n   486→\n   487→## 2. Issues Analysis\n   488→\n   489→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Verification\n   490→\n   491→| Severity | Story | Issue | Fixed? |\n   492→|----------|-------|-------|--------|\n   493→| MEDIUM | 10-4 | Misleading JSDoc in `hasCargoDep` -- example was backwards | Yes |\n   494→| MEDIUM | 10-4 | Missing false-positive prevention tests for crate substring matching -- 2 tests added | Yes |\n   495→\n   496→Code review caught 2 MEDIUM issues, both fixed in-session. No HIGH-severity bugs this time -- the Rust provider had a cleaner implementation compared to Node.js and Python providers.\n   497→\n   498→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n   499→\n   500→1. **`hasCargoDep` matches commented-out dependencies.** Pre-existing behavior inherited from the pattern used in `stack-detect.ts` and other providers. LOW severity, consistent with the same issue in Python and Node.js providers.\n   501→2. **`getCargoDepsSection` doesn't handle `[dependencies.foo]` subsection format.** TOML allows `[dependencies.foo]` as an alternative to inline table syntax. The current regex only handles the `[dependencies]` section block. Pre-existing limitation, not introduced by this story.\n   502→3. **Bevy system libs detection deferred.** Story notes mention Bevy detection for Docker system libs, but no such logic exists in `dockerfile-template.ts`. Correctly deferred to avoid scope creep.\n   503→\n   504→### Code Quality Concerns\n   505→\n   506→1. **Coverage gap: no integration test for `installOtlp` success path.** Requires `cargo` binary. Same pattern as Python provider's `pip`/`pipx` gap. Consistent limitation across all providers.\n   507→2. **`AppType` union lacks `'library'` variant.** Epic definition mentioned it for Rust, but actual code only has `'generic'`. Story creation agent correctly followed the code, not the aspirational epic text.\n   508→\n   509→### Verification Gaps\n   510→\n   511→- **10-4 verification was implicit.** The story was committed with all tests passing (55 new, 3397 total, 0 regressions). Sprint-status shows `done`. However, the session issues log does not record a formal verification stage for 10-4 -- the review stage at 09:34Z was the last recorded pipeline step.\n   512→- **10-5 create-story flagged 3 risks** that the dev agent should watch for:\n   513→  - AC17 (`verify-prompt.ts`) compares `AppType` not `StackName` -- could cause false positives in boundary tests\n   514→  - AC16 (`teardown.ts`) accesses state field not local variable -- migration needs state shape understanding\n   515→  - `detectAppType()` export chain may break if `stack-detect.ts` deleted before re-export verified\n   516→\n   517→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n   518→\n   519→- No sandbox, permission, or CLI issues reported in these sessions.\n   520→- Docker Desktop status remains unknown (not tested in 10-4 since all 27 ACs are `cli-verifiable`).\n   521→\n   522→---\n   523→\n   524→## 3. What Went Well\n   525→\n   526→- **10-4 completed cleanly.** 55 new tests, zero regressions, 2 review issues (both MEDIUM, both fixed). The cleanest provider implementation across all four (10-1 through 10-4).\n   527→- **All 27 ACs verified as `cli-verifiable`.** No Docker dependency needed. The verification-tier pattern from session 11 is now standard.\n   528→- **Story creation agent handled ambiguity well.** Three points of ambiguity in the epic definition (library AppType, Bevy detection, workspace ordering) were all resolved correctly by following the actual codebase rather than aspirational epic text.\n   529→- **Epic 10 at 80% completion.** Four of five stories done in sessions 8-13. The StackProvider pattern (interface + registry + Node.js + Python + Rust) is fully implemented.\n   530→- **Test suite continues to grow.** 3098 -> 3397 (+299 new tests across sessions 8-13). Zero regressions throughout.\n   531→- **10-5 story spec is thorough.** 17 ACs covering every consumer file, with boundary tests (AC12-13) to enforce zero stack string comparisons outside `src/lib/stacks/`. This gives the dev agent strong guidance for the final migration.\n   532→\n   533→---\n   534→\n   535→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   536→\n   537→- **10-4 lacks a formal verification record.** The session issues log shows dev-story at 09:24Z with no issues and code-review at 09:34Z, but no explicit verification stage. Sprint-status shows `done`, so verification must have happened, but there is no proof document or verification log entry. This is a process gap.\n   538→- **Comment-matching in dependency detection is now tech debt across all three providers.** `hasCargoDep`, `hasPythonDep`, and the Node.js equivalent all match package names inside comments. This was flagged as LOW in each review and deferred each time. It is now a systematic issue, not an isolated one.\n   539→- **Story 10-5 is accumulating scope from all prior sessions.** It now owns: consumer migration for 8+ files, type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), stack-detect.ts deletion, import migration for 7+ test files, boundary test creation, and the `StackDetection` type deduplication. This is the largest story in Epic 10 by far.\n   540→- **`installOtlp` success path is untested in all three providers.** This is a systematic gap -- no provider has integration tests for actual package installation. The gap will persist until a CI/Docker environment is available for integration testing.\n   541→\n   542→---\n   543→\n   544→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   545→\n   546→### Repeat\n   547→- **Following actual code over aspirational epic text.** The story creation agent's decision to use `'generic'` instead of `'library'` for Rust and to defer Bevy detection prevented scope creep and kept the story focused.\n   548→- **Consistent provider implementation pattern.** The Rust provider followed the same structure as Node.js and Python, making it the fastest and cleanest implementation. The pattern is proven.\n   549→- **Expanding minimal story specs before development.** The 10-5 create-story stage produced a 17-AC spec from a backlog item with no detail. This is now standard practice across sessions 8-13.\n   550→\n   551→### Avoid\n   552→- **Systematic deferral of the same issue across stories.** Comment-matching in dependency detection was flagged LOW and deferred in 10-2, 10-3, and 10-4. Three deferrals of the same issue should trigger a tracked fix, not another deferral.\n   553→- **Skipping formal verification for stories that \"obviously pass.\"** Even when all tests pass and code review is clean, the verification stage should produce a record. Story 10-4 has no verification artifact.\n   554→\n   555→---\n   556→\n   557→## 6. Action Items\n   558→\n   559→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   560→1. **Verify that 10-4 proof/verification artifact exists.** If not, document the gap. Do not retroactively create a fake proof.\n   561→\n   562→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   563→1. **Complete story 10-5 (consumer migration).** This is the final story in Epic 10. It is large -- consider whether it can be completed in a single session or needs splitting.\n   564→2. **Evaluate splitting 10-5.** Carried forward from sessions 9-11. The story now has at least 5 distinct concerns: (a) consumer file migration, (b) test file import migration, (c) stack-detect.ts deletion, (d) type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), (e) boundary test creation. Consider splitting into 2-3 sub-stories if the dev agent struggles.\n   565→3. **Address the 10-5 risks flagged by create-story.** The `verify-prompt.ts` AppType vs StackName distinction, `teardown.ts` state field access, and `detectAppType()` export chain all need careful handling during implementation.\n   566→4. **Fix comment-matching in dependency detection.** This is now a systematic issue across all providers. Create a single fix that adds comment-awareness to `hasCargoDep`, `hasPythonDep`, and the Node.js equivalent. Track as a backlog item at minimum.\n   567→\n   568→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   569→1. **`installOtlp` integration tests for all providers.** Requires Docker/CI. Systematic gap across Node.js, Python, Rust.\n   570→2. **`getCargoDepsSection` `[dependencies.foo]` subsection format.** TOML edge case, low real-world impact.\n   571→3. **Add `'library'` to `AppType` union.** If Rust library projects need distinct treatment in the future.\n   572→4. **Story 15-4: Fix pre-existing TS compilation errors.** Still at ~50 errors. Noise is chronic.\n   573→5. All items from sessions 8-11 backlog remain open (15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test, `_resetRegistry` export cleanup, readTextSafe catch branch, registry.ts 94.73%, hasPythonDep normalization, TOML regex replacement, proof parser docs).\n   574→\n   575→---\n   576→\n   577→## Cross-Session Summary (Sessions 8-13, 2026-03-24)\n   578→\n   579→### Stories completed today: 4\n   580→- **10-1-stackprovider-interface-and-registry** -- done (session 8)\n   581→- **10-2-nodejs-provider** -- done (session 9)\n   582→- **10-3-python-provider** -- done (sessions 10-11)\n   583→- **10-4-rust-provider** -- done (sessions 12-13)\n   584→\n   585→### Stories started: 1\n   586→- **10-5-migrate-consumers-to-stackprovider** -- ready-for-dev (story created in session 13)\n   587→\n   588→### Cumulative stats\n   589→- Tests: 3098 -> 3397 (+299 new tests)\n   590→- Bugs caught by code review: 17 (7 in session 8, 4 in session 9, 4 in session 10, 2 in sessions 12-13) -- all fixed\n   591→- Bugs shipped: 0\n   592→- Stories blocked: 0\n   593→- Tech debt items deferred: 11 (type mismatches x2, regex fragility x3, comment matching x3, task markers, consumer branches, AGENTS.md staleness)\n   594→\n   595→### Sprint velocity\n   596→- Epic 10 progress: 0/5 -> 4/5 in one day (6 sessions)\n   597→- Pipeline throughput: ~1 story per ralph session (consistent across all 6 sessions)\n   598→- Estimated sessions remaining for Epic 10: 1 (10-5 only, but it is the largest story)\n   599→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_018RJZitN2HYhaE97pNMBo57","session_id":"6707468c-554d-4568-9ea5-0d04d4a85f59","uuid":"41df5374-7498-4413-9aa5-aa2b2f5f29da","timestam